 in 1068 or 1070 in the retinue of Queen Margaret. She was an English princess who had been born and brought up in Hungary and who went on to marry King Malcolm III of Scotland. Members of the clan have held several titles in the peerage of Scotland, including Earl of Rothes (from 1437)."],"variants":[{"name":"Leece","meanings":["English: from a medieval female personal name, <i>Lece</i>, a short form of <i>Lettice</i> (from Latin <i>Laetitia</i>, meaning ‘happiness, gaiety’).","English: variant of   Lees  .","Irish: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Íosa</i>, Manx <i>Mac Guilley Yeesey</i> ‘son of <i>Giolla Íosa</i> (devotee or servant of Jesus)’. Ballaleece (‘Leece's farm’) in Kirk German was the family's main seat."]},{"name":"Lesslie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Lesley","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Laslie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Lessley","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Lasley","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leslie  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel Leslie was born in 1280, in Edinburgh, Scotland. She married John Crichton in 1301, in Edinburgh, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1357, in Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1280–1357":"1280–1357","1278–1357":"1278–1357","1304–1382":"1304–1382","1304":"1304","1357":"1357","1301":"1301","1278":"1278","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland","Crichton Castle, Pathhead, East Lothia